INT. FEDERAL COMPLIANCE FIELD OFFICE - DAY

A converted storefront. Folding tables, a space heater, a laminated poster on the wall: HARMONY IS A VERB — above it, a photo plaque, Q3 COMPLIANCE EXCELLENCE AWARD, Pell two years younger holding it with both hands like a fish.

Pell at a folding desk, laptop open on a call. On the screen: DIRECTOR HOLLOWAY, gray, unreadable, better light than this room has.

PELL:
(bright, reading off a checklist)
Dawes parcel, closed this morning. Apparatus recovered, tagged federal interest. Full cooperation on-site. Well — cooperation.

HOLLOWAY (ON SCREEN):
That's one.

PELL:
It's a significant one, sir. Fifty years of unlogged—

HOLLOWAY (ON SCREEN):
(not really listening, flipping something off-screen)
Ohio's regional is at six this week. You're regional too. Forty-one parcels flagged, one closure since binding. That's the number I'm reading right now, off a spreadsheet, with your name on the tab.

Pell's smile holds a half-second too long.

PELL:
Understood. I'll accelerate the schedule.

HOLLOWAY (ON SCREEN):
Accelerate it before the Fourth. I've got a call in nine minutes.

The screen goes to the call's end card before Pell can answer. He sits a moment, the dead laptop reflecting the fluorescent tubes overhead.

Then he pulls the district binder over, flips past DAWES, E. — CLOSED, and runs his finger down a long column of names. He stops on one, uncaps a highlighter, and drags it across the line, slow, hard enough to bleed through the page.

INSERT — THE BINDER: a column of names and addresses. One now bright yellow: HOLLENBECK GRAIN & FEED — FLAGGED, PRIORITY REVIEW.

Pell closes the binder. Squares it on the desk. Takes his lanyard off the hook by the door, and puts it back on.

CUT TO:
